src/main/java/com/MyApp/
├── model/         → Your entity classes (maps to DB tables)
├── repository/    → Database access layer
├── service/       → Business logic
├── controller/    → HTTP endpoints (REST API)
└── Application.java  → Entry point
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Integer type instead of int for ids because it defaults to null instead of 0


@Column(...)
puts constraints on a certain column


Spring data jpa thingy:
- Repo abstraction is an interface that extends one of spring data jpa repo interfaces used to reduce boilerplate code needed to implement the DAO to interact with the data stores
its used to abstract the data acces layer from business logic, used to perfrom CRUD operations.

- It has 3 Main interfaces:
    CRUD
    sorting
    paging
==> Main use is interacting with the database (perform operations)


=== Flow
    - Controller → calls → Service → calls → Repository

    -Repository — talks to the database directly. Only knows how to fetch/save/delete data. No business logic.

    - Service — contains the business logic. It uses the repository to get data, then     does something with it. It doesn't        implement the repository, it calls it.

    - Controller — receives the HTTP request,   calls the service, sends the result to    the Thymeleaf page.
































